### Culture

#### Miami Dialect

In [Miami-Dade County](/Miami-Dade_County,_Florida), a distinct dialect, commonly known as the Miami accent, is widely spoken. This dialect emerged among second and third-generation [Hispanics](/Hispanic_and_Latino_Americans), particularly [Cuban-Americans](/Cuban-American), whose first language was [English](/English_(language)). Elements of this accent have also been adopted by some [non-Hispanic white](/Non-Hispanic_white), [black](/Black_people), and individuals of other races who were born and raised in Miami-Dade. The accent is rooted in a relatively [standard American accent](/General_American) but incorporates distinctive features influenced by dialects of the [Mid-Atlantic](/Mid-Atlantic_States), especially those found in the [New York area dialect](/New_York_City_English), [Northern New Jersey English](/New_Jersey_English), and [New York Latino English](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York_Latino_English). Unlike certain other American dialects, the Miami accent is [rhotic](/Rhotic_and_non-rhotic_accents). It also integrates a rhythm and pronunciation heavily influenced by [Spanish](/Spanish_(language)), a language characterized by its syllable-timed rhythm.

Distinguishing the Miami accent from the [interlanguages](/Interlanguage) spoken by second-language learners is possible. The Miami accent typically does not exhibit the addition of /ɛ/ before initial consonant clusters with /s/, speakers do not confuse /dʒ/ with /j/ (e.g., saying "jail" instead of "yale"), and the sounds /r/ and /rr/ are pronounced as an [alveolar approximant](/Alveolar_approximant) [ɹ] rather than the [alveolar tap](/Alveolar_tap) [ɾ] or [alveolar trill](/Alveolar_trill) [r] found in Spanish.

The Miami accent is considerably less prevalent in [Broward County](/Broward_County) and [Palm Beach County](/Palm_Beach_County), areas where the majority of the population is non-Hispanic.

