#### Media

Greater Miami is a significant media market, served by multiple [English-language](/English_language) and two major [Spanish-language](/Spanish_language) daily newspapers. [The Miami Herald](/The_Miami_Herald), headquartered in [Doral](/Doral,_Florida), is the region's primary newspaper, boasting over a million readers. It maintains news bureaus in [Broward County](/Broward_County), [Monroe County](/Monroe_County,_Florida), and [Nassau, Bahamas](/Nassau,_Bahamas). The [South Florida Sun-Sentinel](/South_Florida_Sun-Sentinel) primarily circulates in Broward and southern Palm Beach counties and also has a news bureau in Havana, Cuba. [The Palm Beach Post](/The_Palm_Beach_Post) focuses on Palm Beach County, particularly its central and northern regions, and the [Treasure Coast](/Treasure_Coast). The [Boca Raton News](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boca_Raton_News) publishes five days a week, serving southern Palm Beach County. [El Nuevo Herald](/El_Nuevo_Herald), an affiliate of the Miami Herald, and [Diario Las Americas](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diario_Las_Am%C3%A9ricas), are prominent Spanish-language daily newspapers circulating mainly in Miami-Dade County. Weekly Spanish newspapers, La Palma and [El Sentinel](/El_Sentinel_del_Sur_de_la_Florida), published by the Palm Beach Post and Sun-Sentinel respectively, cover the same geographical areas as their English counterparts.

Several university student newspapers also contribute to the local media landscape, including [The Miami Hurricane](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Miami_Hurricane) at the [University of Miami](/University_of_Miami), [University Press](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_Press_(Florida_Atlantic_University)) at [Florida Atlantic University](/Florida_Atlantic_University), [PantherNOW](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PantherNOW) at [Florida International University](/Florida_International_University), and [The Current](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Current_(NSU)) at [Nova Southeastern University](/Nova_Southeastern_University).

Greater Miami is divided into two distinct television and radio markets: the Miami-Fort Lauderdale market, which serves Miami-Dade, Broward, and the Florida Keys; and the West Palm Beach market, covering Palm Beach County and the [Treasure Coast](/Treasure_Coast) region.

The Miami-Fort Lauderdale market ranks as the 12th largest radio market and the 16th-largest television market in the U.S. Key television stations serving this area include [WAMI-TV](/WAMI-TV) (UniMas), [WBFS-TV](/WBFS-TV) (The CW), [WSFL-TV](/WSFL-TV) (Independent), [WFOR-TV](/WFOR-TV) (CBS), [WHFT-TV](/WHFT-TV) (TBN), [WLTV](/WLTV) (Univision), [WPLG](/WPLG) (Independent), [WPXM](/WPXM) (ION), [WSCV](/WSCV) (Telemundo), [WSVN](/WSVN) (FOX, with ABC on DT2), [WTVJ](/WTVJ) (NBC), [WLRN-TV](/WLRN-TV) (PBS), and [WPBT](/WPBT) (also PBS). The latter two PBS stations are unique in serving the entire metropolitan area.

Beyond the Miami-Fort Lauderdale market, West Palm Beach has its own distinct media landscape. It ranks as the 49th largest radio market and the 38th-largest television market in the U.S. Television stations broadcasting in the West Palm Beach area include [WPTV](/WPTV) (NBC), [WHDT](/WHDT) (Independent), [WPEC](/WPEC) (CBS), [WPBF](/WPBF) (ABC), [WFLX](/WFLX) (FOX), [WTVX](/WTVX) (The CW), [WXEL](/WXEL-TV) (PBS), and [WPXP](/WPXP) (ION). Both the West Palm Beach and Miami-Fort Lauderdale markets share access to WSCV and WLTV for Telemundo and Univision programming, respectively. Additionally, programming from both markets is often available interchangeably across areas. In 2015, WPBT and WXEL merged their operations to form [South Florida PBS](/South_Florida_PBS), maintaining separate programming schedules and social media platforms while sharing the same subchannel lineup.

### Education

In Florida, each county functions as its own [school district](/School_district), overseen by an elected [school board](/School_board). The day-to-day management of each district is handled by a professional [superintendent](/Superintendent_(education)), appointed by and serving at the pleasure of the school board.

The [Miami-Dade County Public School District](/Miami-Dade_County_Public_Schools) is recognized as the [4th-largest public school district](/List_of_the_largest_school_districts_in_the_United_States_by_enrollment) in the nation. Similarly, the [School District of Palm Beach County](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/School_District_of_Palm_Beach_County) ranks as the 4th-largest in Florida and the 11th-largest nationally. [Broward County Public School District](/Broward_County_Public_Schools) holds the distinction of being the 6th-largest in the United States.

The [University of Miami](/University_of_Miami), a private research institution, is consistently ranked among the top universities in the United States and possesses the most selective admissions criteria among Florida's 171 colleges and universities.

As of 2023, [Florida International University](/Florida_International_University), with an enrollment exceeding 55,000 students, ranks as the [eighth-largest public university by enrollment](/List_of_United_States_university_campuses_by_enrollment) nationwide.

