#### Seaports

The metropolitan area is home to four significant seaports. The most prominent among these is the [Port of Miami](/Port_of_Miami), which holds the distinction of being the world's busiest cruise ship port. Other key ports in the area include [Port Everglades](/Port_Everglades), the [Port of Palm Beach](/Port_of_Palm_Beach), and the [Miami River](/Miami_River_(Florida)) Port. In a significant development, PortMiami and the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers signed a Partnership Agreement in August 2012 for the Deep Dredge project. This project aims to deepen the port's existing channels to a depth of minus 50/52 feet, preparing it to accommodate larger vessels following the expansion of the Panama Canal, which was slated for completion in early 2015. The deepened channel will provide ships with an efficient, reliable, and safe navigational route into the port. PortMiami is projected to be the only U.S. port south of Norfolk, Virginia, capable of handling such depths concurrently with the expanded canal. The Deep Dredge project is anticipated to generate over 30,000 direct, indirect, and induced jobs in Florida and support the port's objective of doubling its cargo traffic within a decade.

#### Public Transportation

[Miami-Dade Transit](/Miami-Dade_Transit) stands as Florida's largest public transit agency, operating a comprehensive network of [rapid transit](/Rapid_transit) lines, [people movers](/People_mover), and an [intercity bus](/Intercity_bus) system. Metrorail, Florida's sole [rapid transit](/Rapid_transit) system, currently features 23 stations along a 24.4-mile (39.3 km) track. The [Downtown Miami](/Greater_Downtown_Miami) [people mover](/People_mover), known as Metromover, comprises 20 stations across three lines on a 4.4-mile (7.1 km) track, serving the [neighborhoods](/Neighborhoods_of_Miami) of the [Arts & Entertainment District](/Arts_%26_Entertainment_District), the [Central Business District](/Central_Business_District_(Miami)), and [Brickell](/Brickell). Metrobus provides service throughout Miami-Dade County, extending into [Monroe County](/Monroe_County,_Florida) as far south as [Marathon](/Marathon,_Florida), and into [Broward County](/Broward_County,_Florida), reaching as far north as Downtown Fort Lauderdale. In Broward County, [Broward County Transit](/Broward_County_Transit) operates the public bus system, while [Palm Tran](/Palm_Tran) serves Palm Beach County. Additionally, the [South Florida Regional Transportation Authority](/South_Florida_Regional_Transportation_Authority) manages Tri-Rail, a commuter rail service connecting the major cities of Miami, Fort Lauderdale, and West Palm Beach, along with intermediate stations. [Brightline](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brightline) offers intercity rail service to [Miami](/Miami), [Aventura](/Aventura,_Florida), [West Palm Beach](/West_Palm_Beach,_Florida), [Fort Lauderdale](/Fort_Lauderdale,_Florida), [Boca Raton](/Boca_Raton,_Florida), and connects to Central Florida's [Orlando](/Orlando,_Florida). Discussions are also underway for potential expansions to [Tampa](/Tampa) and [Jacksonville](/Jacksonville,_Florida).

